{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17478952","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17478952"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-28T23:17:36+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-28T23:17:36+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18850"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"18850","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/18850"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.54,0.11,0.04,0.15,0.17]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11583"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"79706"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"11583","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/11583"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18850"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"65010"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"9"},{"type":"tags","id":"14"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"36"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1061"},{"type":"tags","id":"1155"},{"type":"tags","id":"1239"},{"type":"tags","id":"2891"},{"type":"tags","id":"4954"},{"type":"tags","id":"4966"},{"type":"tags","id":"9713"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11638"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"27254"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44230"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"79706","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/79706"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA seven-year-old boy presents to the Emergency Department with a two-day history of right-sided testicular pain and swelling. He developed facial swelling and fever six days ago. He has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. His immunisations are not up to date as his parents declined the measles-mumps-rubella vaccine.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears uncomfortable. His pulse rate is 100/min, blood pressure 110/70 mmHg, respiratory rate 20/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 38.2\u00b0C. There is bilateral parotid swelling. The right hemiscrotum is swollen and tender, but not erythematous. The cremasteric reflex is present bilaterally.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Supportive care with analgesia","Oral amoxicillin-clavulanate","Urgent surgical exploration","Intravenous ceftriaxone","Scrotal ultrasound"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with orchitis secondary to mumps infection, as evidenced by the preceding parotitis and unvaccinated status. Mumps orchitis typically develops 4-7 days after the onset of parotitis and is the most common cause of prepubertal orchitis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESupportive care with analgesia\u003C/strong\u003E is the most appropriate management for mumps orchitis. The condition is self-limiting and typically resolves within 3-10 days. Treatment includes rest, scrotal support, ice packs, and appropriate pain relief.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EUrgent surgical exploration\u003C/strong\u003E would be indicated if testicular torsion was suspected. However, the presence of bilateral parotitis, the timing of symptoms, and the presence of cremasteric reflexes make torsion unlikely in this case.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIntravenous ceftriaxone\u003C/strong\u003E would be appropriate for bacterial orchitis, which is usually secondary to epididymitis and associated with urinary tract infection or anatomical abnormalities. The clinical picture here is not consistent with bacterial infection.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOral amoxicillin-clavulanate\u003C/strong\u003E would also be inappropriate as antibiotics are not effective against the mumps virus and there are no signs of bacterial infection.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EScrotal ultrasound\u003C/strong\u003E is not necessary when the diagnosis of mumps orchitis is clear from the clinical presentation. Ultrasound would be indicated if there was diagnostic uncertainty or concern about torsion.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EPrevention through vaccination is key, as mumps orchitis can occasionally lead to testicular atrophy and fertility problems. This case highlights the importance of completing the recommended vaccination schedule.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Mumps orchitis is the most common cause of prepubertal orchitis and typically occurs 4-7 days after parotitis.","Bacterial orchitis in children is usually secondary to epididymitis and requires appropriate antibiotic therapy.","Testicular torsion must be excluded in any child presenting with acute testicular pain."],"references":["Trojian TH, Lishnak TS, Heiman D. Epididymitis and orchitis: An overview. Am Fam Physician. 2009;79(7):583-587."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"65010"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18850"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"65010","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/65010"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-15T13:12:00+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-15T13:12:56+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11583"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"79706"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"9","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/9"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc76","name":"Paediatrics","synonyms":[],"description":n